Colin Green wrote:

&gt;To be fair on the experiments I 
&gt;should steepen that activation function 
&gt;

Here&#39;s a steepened sigmoid...

if( x &lt; -0x20000000 )
{
    return 0x0;
}
else if( x &lt; 0x0 )
{
    int tmp = (x&gt;&gt;17) + 0x1000;
    return ((tmp*tmp)&gt;&gt;13);
}
else if( x &lt; 0x20000000 )
{
    int tmp = (x&gt;&gt;17) - 0x1000;
    return 0x1000 - ((tmp*tmp)&gt;&gt;13;
}
else
{
    return 0x1000;
}



Note that I use two rotates to calculate the value, whereas in fact you 
could get away with increasing the first one and dropping the 2nd, but 
this would result in precision being lost. Again, if you were trying to 
squeeze out extra CPU cyles from network code then you might consider 
such variations. You would also hope that a decent optimiser would 
optimise out the tmp variable (e.g. use a CPU register only) rather than 
allocating memory.

Colin.
